WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Today is Thursday, June 9, 2011. My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:27.000
I'm with theographer John Bishop. We are in the Orangeburg South Carolina to complete an oral history interview

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:38.000
for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And we're delighted today to be with you, Mr. Cecil J. Williams. It's an honor and a privilege. Thank you for sitting down with us and welcoming us to your home and studio for this opportunity.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
It's my great pleasure as well.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:01:02.000
I'm just very much looking forward to the session today. So let me start our conversation with... can you just give a basic description of your childhood and youth and family and early education?

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Well, I am the third sibling of Ethel and Cecil J. Williams. My father, who has, of course, and mother had passed away, but he was a self-employed tailor, worked in the city of Orangeburg.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:28.000
My mother, all of her life, was an educator. She worked on a college level as well as a high school and a elementary level.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:42.000
And I grew up in Orangeburg. This has been my home, my life's home. And I have preferred to remain here in spite of all the negative things and the...

00:01:42.000 --> 00:02:01.000
in spite of the fact that this has been really the beginning and still is somewhat of a battleground for my race and trying to overcome all the barriers that arrive out of...

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:14.000
just trying to make a living and growing up in a... the segregation that I did grew up in under Jim Crow laws that affected the state of South Carolina.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:27.000
But my mother taught me at a very early age that really that mostly people are like. We're more like than we are different.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:37.000
And I grew up understanding. And I tried to treat all people of all races, all of my life as she did as fair as I could.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:48.000
And I think that her lessons and my father's lessons, I think have helped to make me the person that I am today.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:03:00.000
But I become aware I was going on relative to race and civil rights probably around seven or eight or nine years old.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:11.000
As a youth, I remembered boarding. At that time we had a bus system here in Orangeburg, bus transportation system.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:23.000
And I remember boarding the bus and my awareness of segregation probably came about as she told me that we had to sit in a certain section of the bus.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:36.000
So we would usually... sometimes it changed. Sometimes it was that we were sit at the back of the bus and sometimes it was that we would have to sit maybe a certain section in the bus.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And it very definitely had a line that bought where we were to sit. It was either within that line and if the bus was crowded and where we were to sit was crowded, then we had to stand or not board the bus at all.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And so this was probably my very first lesson or experience in race and where we were to... we had a place.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:23.000
So largely I grew up thinking that really Orangeburg, the citizens here, the white citizens, the black citizens, we lived in very parallel societies, a white society, a black society.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:41.000
And there were separate playgrounds, separate schools. If we went to a movie theater, there was a place designated for African Americans. We either sat upstairs or downstairs. And it changed.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:52.000
If we were to go into a store in downtown Orangeburg, we could go into the main store but if there's a lunch counter, we could not sit down at the lunch counter.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Of course I'm speaking about the period as I became an adult and as I became co-owns of my surroundings, the fifties, of course the early sixties.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:16.000
If we were to say take a bus from the Orangeburg Greyhound Trailway Station, of course we would then also have to sit on that particular bus.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And so interstate transportation was also segregated. We had a certain place that we could... we would have to sit.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:45.000
The school system that I grew up under from all the days that I was in education was also segregated. I went to the segregated elementary schools, segregated middle schools, segregated high school. My high school was Wilkinson High School.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:06:07.000
So this kind of gives you an overview of my growing up in and around Orangeburg. And my family lived on Quick Street. I grew up on an area of Orangeburg that would be about two blocks from South Carolina State College.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:21.000
And it was in the shadows of those colleges that my entire world, whatever experiences I had, were greatly influenced by the colleges.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And I would say that Orangeburg would be much less a significant place as it turned out to be, had it not been for the influence of those colleges, Claflin and South Carolina State College.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:53.000
South Carolina State and Claflin College helped to really feel my experiences of life from the standpoint that they brought in cultural programs and speakers from the outside world, some internationally known.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:01.000
And they feel that helped to round out my experiences from not living in a city of significant size.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:19.000
Orangeburg, a largely agricultural community, we are about midways between Columbia, South Carolina and Charleston, South Carolina, Columbia being the capital, and Charleston being also a very significant area in a large population as well.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:29.000
Well, see, approximately a percentage of the local population in the city in the town back in the 50s, black and white.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Roughly about 40% of African American, yes.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And you mentioned the two colleges and how significant those were to as institutions in the black community and in the city's life, in the towns life and in those days and now.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:50.000
Where was your father's tailor shop and how did it relate to was there any tech black business community in the South of Detroit?

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:59.000
No, a business like tailoring and certain other businesses somehow enjoyed a very unique position.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:13.000
For example, my father's business was almost entirely 80% clientele clientele were white and he worked for the, he did the alterations for the downtown stores.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:23.000
Bill Hudson, as it was called, that doing those days, Bar Shays, Lime House, Men's Stores.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:28.000
And I worked doing the summer months and then sometimes on weekends I worked for my father.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:37.000
I didn't ever learn how to, they do any tailoring, but I did deliver the clothes back to the stores after he finished the alterations.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:43.000
And then I would take, at the end of the week, take the bills and go to the stores and collect the money.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:48.000
And then my father would give me my little weekly allowance that way as well.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:59.000
You got a camera when you were still, I don't even think 10 years old and that would obviously in some ways set you on the course that they came to your life's work.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So maybe you could recall the color of your first camera and how you moved forward from that.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:11.000
Yes, my first camera which was given to me by, I think my brother, my brother had inherited the camera, I think my mother had purchased the camera.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:16.000
A Kodak baby brown, which I still have and by the way, which still works.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:27.000
But it was, as my brother's interest grew to music and blowing a saxophone, he gave me the camera and of course I started taking pictures.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And I was fascinated by the fact that you could capture an image and then see it.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:40.000
And it was much later in my life that I discovered of course how to set up a dark room and develop in my own pictures.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:46.000
But as I took pictures from people on Sundays, I would have them develop.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:52.000
And this also became my hustle because I could earn a dollar or two on Sundays of people dressed up in their finalies.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:10:03.000
And it is still gardens which is a local garden where we have a coarse water running, the it is still river runs through it.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:19.000
And we have many rows and other varieties of things growing and it becomes a very popular place for both black and white citizens of course to go there and walk around the gardens and take pictures and lay on the grass.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:27.000
And this one was a very unpopular place. And incidentally it was open to people who were all races at the time as well.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:36.000
There was one of the places. So it had very unusual kinds of barriers.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:43.000
Again a place like that was open but curiously a driving theater was close to blacks.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:52.000
So since we would arrive in your own automobile but blacks could not go to drive ins.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:02.000
But yet we could go to the stationary establishment but we would just sit upstairs or downstairs as it was sometimes.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:14.000
The Edistowe Theater and there was also a black movie theater at the time which was right across the street from South Carolina State and Clafer University.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:25.000
And on Saturdays as a youth with my box of popcorn I would sit in there and watch the great movies of those days.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And the series of movies that came out like Captain Midnight and Captain Marvel and the Phantom and Roy Rogers and Dale Evans and Jean Archie.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:50.000
And the series would be that the main character would get into some kind of trouble and almost reach the end of his.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:58.000
He would have some perilous situation in which it would occur. But you'd have to come back next week to see what ultimately outcome.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:11.000
And so I grew up with that kind of background. Of course it was a culture that was developing right underneath my very eyes of being a soci...

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:33.000
being receiving experiences from of course of motion pictures. Motion pictures were a very important part of my development as a person because it would be a aspiring photographer, the imagery of how that was done.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And the process itself I remember seeing at a very early age going with the wind which at that time was a great accomplishment in a cinema production.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:13:03.000
And MGM producing this very long motion picture that really depicted the old South. The fact of the changes coming as noted by the name going with the wind.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:13.000
Would you say that your household was a race conscious household with civil rights or race issues things that you talked about around the dinner table?

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:20.000
Or was it obviously it was something that was active and alive in the community? Was it at your dinner table?

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:34.000
Yes, but we did not encounter these barriers until of course we left our... what I thought was a very comfortable household.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:45.000
And I don't think I could ever say that there was one day when even though my family was low income I don't think there was ever one day that we didn't have to eat what we wanted to eat.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:14:00.000
So my I have a very caring parents and grandparents as it turned out as sometimes my mother and father were leaving the custody of my grandmother who was of course again very wise.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:08.000
She had the wisdom of course years of living under her entire life she grew up under segregation.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:26.000
But from my mother's side we grew up also with another kind of denominator that was kind of puzzling because we were a mixed race in my father's side Indian and black in my mother's side black and white.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:38.000
So this was kind of puzzling because my mother was of a skin color that if you saw her you would not know what race she was.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And my father of course with coming with an Indian background Indian and black so it was very confusing to a youth of eight or nine years old as to where to fit.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:15:20.000
And how to fit into this very mixed bag of racial placement that we had to adhere to or abide by or the other thing that was puzzling was that the fact that I grew up at a time when all this was state sanctioned segregation.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:44.000
Legal segregation so a little difference between I think that kind of segregation and maybe a second in some other type of segregation but legal segregation where the state and I guess the nation the county the county puts up signs in the courthouse that says white water fountain colored water fountain.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:16:13.000
The state which runs the schools in the city which runs the schools as you can't go to this particular school if you are colored so the places where we were able to go to school or shot take a bus we had federal state city and county regulation of these laws that effective.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:26.000
Yes that effective me as African American growing up doing the time yes when did you first connect your camera.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:55.000
Well probably around 12 or 13 years old maybe even I was born in 1937 yes maybe even earlier but looking back and when I was gathering information for the books that I have published this was something that I also was kind of trying to connect and get all the dates right but of course my

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:24.000
a lot of my photographs begin of course in my own household and a family and it's a rounding area but probably around 11 or 12 years old I have a mentor EC Jones from Sumter South Carolina and he was called into take photographs of the churches of Clarence and County where the Briggs and Delayne and Pearson

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:53.000
families are beginning of battle that becomes really the catalyst of the Briggs versus Elliot petition and Jones found out that I was a photographer and that I had a camera and of course he would sometimes pick me up from Sumter and take me into those church meetings on Sunday and there we began taking what we were doing.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:13.000
So that became the photographs that appear in many books today of the Briggs petitioners the Delayne family and I grew up you know seeing this happening but not totally understanding what was going on.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:32.000
Yes and a lot of times Jones's studio by the name was Majestic Studio and sometimes in the pictures that I might have taken sometimes the ones that he took you might see his camera which had on again Majestic Studio.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:19:01.000
Sumter was a very important city at that time because we had the the Air Force base there and Jones would purchase the out of date film supplies and paper supplies and then he would give that to me and as I began to develop my dog get my dog one going he would also sometimes kind of compensate me for my time and as he became the official photographer South Carolina State College he pulled me into of course taking pictures for state

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:27.000
because if I could take pictures at state college that would save him 80 mile round trip coming from Sumter but as the NAACP and J.A. Delayne called him into action of course and then of course I accompanied him and that's how many of the photographs that we come up with relatives to Briggs versus Elliott.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:31.000
That case those are how they were those came about.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:37.000
Two questions one quick aside how did you first become connected to Mr. Jones.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:52.000
Well Mr. Jones was a very close friend of my at one time my high school principal and one time my high school teacher Mr. Robert Howard they were of course at one time students at South Carolina State College.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:20:08.000
So Mr. Howard recommended to Jones that of course he knew I had a camera and my better cameras by the way were also the cameras that I used at the high school board.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:37.000
For example I remember using the course I was fascinated by film and of course they had the 60 in the middle of the bell and how camera and the four by five crown and speed graphic and the two and a quarter by three and a quarter speed and crown graphic cameras among the cameras that high school allowed me to well not not only high school but actually when I was in 10th 19th grade I was able to use the camera.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:21:06.000
I was able to use those very expensive cameras at the time more so than the cameras that I had I grew up at say at taking photographs with the first camera of course was the baby brownie but it had no flash unit so I could not take a picture of anything that required a flash unit but I think I took my first pictures with a flash unit flash bulb of course I have a picture of third good Marshall coming off the train.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:35.000
Well that was one of the first pictures but it was like but see a flash bulb at the time keep it by a camera or maybe $15 at the time from Sears Roboc but the flash part of it the flash bulb was sort of out of sync because of a flash bulb in comparison to what you could buy a camera for was very expensive and it only flash one time.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:53.000
And it was going and so typically we would I would go and maybe at 13 years old as I did take pictures of waiting and I'm putting 12 pictures in the brides waiting album and I only took 15 pictures of the whole waiting.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:22:18.000
So because they were taking with the flash that was a very expensive part of it but the photograph of third good Marshall coming off the train and happened because the gentleman by the name who was the president of NAACP took me to Charleston because in my mind he had described this big lawyer that was coming down from New York and they had this big trial going on in Charleston South Carolina.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And that's when I took third good Marshall and one of his trips to the south where he got off the civil media and I snapped this picture of him on the civil media.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.000
The president of the state and the ACP then was?

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:38.000
Well the president of the Orangeburg branch at the time was a gentleman by the name of Squire Morgue.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:49.000
And the state at that time I don't know I only became aware of the state presidents of the NAACP at a later.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:50.000
Revenue man.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:58.000
Revenue man of course was also a good friend of Robert Howard and of course he would sometimes come and get me out of school.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:10.000
And so a lot of times my field trips have become really was an exercise in the what was turning out to be the civil rights movement.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:24.000
Sounds fair to say and you can tell me if I'm right that these gentlemen who were at that forefront at front edge of trying to advance the movement recognize even then photographs of this activity can be very helpful.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Yes.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:27.000
And we need to be careful about this and think carefully.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:28.000
Yes.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:32.000
Yes. Also the photographs were necessary because of this.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:42.000
The local newspaper very rarely had news of interest to African Americans at the time to colored people.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:51.000
In fact once in a while there was a section in the paper called news of interest to colored people that would appear once a week and it would just be a little bit.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:24:00.000
But of course any action to demonstrate or protest would never be in there.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:10.000
So it was because of that void that I began taking pictures for the news agencies that reach beyond Orangeburg.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:21.000
So I started taking pictures for the outflow American, the Pittsburgh Correa and of course ultimately a 15 years old I become an official correspondent for Jet Magazine.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:28.000
Jet comes into Orangeburg from Chicago.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:33.000
The story is developing and ongoing and they need somebody to continuously cover it.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:41.000
And at 15 years old they made me a correspondent for a National Magazine.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:55.000
And the money they pay to me at that time $35 for a photograph was a lot of money to a person in my age at that time.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:25:08.000
I want to have you if you would and you were just an adolescent but take us back to one of those meetings in Clare Midd County and describe the people and the atmosphere and the mood and...

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:13.000
Well it takes place in many different time periods.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:21.000
Number one most of the early people involved in the Clarentine County and the Briggs case.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:26.000
Many of them were run away. They lost their jobs and were forced to leave.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:40.000
So a lot of the pictures that Mr. Jones and I took were pictures of celebrations and pictures when they gathered together again at the churches for a commemoration or an awards ceremony.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:49.000
And we came to photograph those ceremonies and those award presentations and gathering of...

00:25:49.000 --> 00:26:07.000
And then sometimes at the request of the newspapers when they were asked together together, of course the entire Briggs petitioners get together at St. Mark and those photographs took place.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:27.000
It's also interesting at this time from the standpoint of most historians is that Clarentine County and Orangebury begin at such an early part of this and really they are the ones that are creating the catalysts from which the base of all the civil rights movement begins.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:51.000
But at this time it's not even known as the civil rights movement. It's so early on into this new found way of saying trying to bring down these barriers that it doesn't seem to become known as the civil rights movement until really about 1955 when Martin Luther King and Rosa Parks with Montgomery Busboy Cut.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:27:14.000
But the Briggs petitioners beginning 10 and 15 years earlier and the Brown versus Board of Education case, the catalysts, the template, the case that really started the Thurgood Marshall and the entire legal arm of the NAWACP,

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:43.000
the NAWACP, all in this direction was created by the Briggs case in Clarentine County starting off in the beginning as a bus transportation effort to get a bus for the children and then later developing in the case went to Charleston, wearing then Thurgood Marshall suddenly becomes aware that this might be it rather than having to go the way the NAWACP was going and having to maybe sue every school.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:56.000
So, if you sue every school district in the entire United States in order to achieve equality and education, it was a case that maybe that might be the template for what they were looking for.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:00.000
Do you remember when Brown came down in May of 54 you were in high school?

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:01.000
When Brown?

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:04.000
When the Brown decision came down in May of 1950.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:05.000
Oh yes, I was, yes, yes.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:09.000
What are your memories of that, of that, of that, of that ripple through the community?

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:23.000
Again, because of the dangers associated with this in the early stages and again the Briggs people you see were forced to leave and the delaying people were forced to remand delaying,

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:33.000
who by the way, my mother taught under the remand delaying and that's also how I have a close association with the lanes because my mother was a school teacher under him.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:54.000
You have this danger aspect of the, that's not often written about, that's associated with it, that you don't really just talk about this because anyone talking about this might find themselves visited by the cookout client or you might find yourself if you're working for,

00:28:54.000 --> 00:29:13.000
see the employment situation was mostly in control of whites and almost everything, any type of employment was really at the mercy of the white leaders.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:25.000
And if you, in any way, were found to be associated with this effort to overthrow their way of life, your livelihood or sometimes your life was also in danger.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:32.000
So I remember to answer specifically your question about what did I think after the Briggs Brown versus Board of Education case occurred.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:46.000
It was one that was sometimes, you know, in very low tones discussed and you only discussed it maybe within the black society that you, and other people that were, that you knew.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:30:05.000
But just generally out there, and now if you're going back to 1956, this was something that was not the celebration that you might think that it would be, that it was the pivotal case that brought this all to a turning point.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:17.000
Yes, fascinating because you already knew from that direct personal experience with these families that the consequences could be so charged with violence, so charged with this, with the ultimate, all these ultimate consequences.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:32.000
And in the small parts of Orangebury County and Ellery and other little cities and camera, you see here you had an extreme form of racism that was also violence attached to it.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:42.000
So there are many kinds of stories that have never been reported about people who just disappeared.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:50.000
I think that kind of violence, that extra-judicial racial violence, the clan, others formally or informally organized.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:57.000
Had that impinged on your immediate family directly or near extended family and your childhood years?

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:25.000
No, my mother and father warned me about it. Some white businessmen went to my father and told him that they advised him to advise me that I better be careful because they began to note that my pictures were appearing in the magazines and newspapers and outside agitators were using me to report on what was going on here.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:52.000
And so probably three times maybe they went to him. And my mother was sort of isolated from it in that she was a part of the school system and knowing what happened to Reverend D'Layne, she often talked to me in a kind of a harsh way because, you see, again, people of my mother and fathers era, and the time they grew up in, they learned to deal with segregation and what was happening all around them.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:32:03.000
And they formed sort of an accommodation type of relationship in a way to get along and also to put bread on the table.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:16.000
If they were actually going out alone, they would be again subject to all kinds of situations which would have interrupted their lives.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:35.000
The unity that they later become a part of in the demonstrations that developed in the late 50s and after in the early 60s, of course, then together they were able to then participate and then join forces.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:47.000
And they lose any individual isolated attempts to antagonize them or fire them or what have you.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:33:03.000
But when it was in the early years, it was very dangerous to, it was again, here are people coming together and we're talking about trying to change the state and federal,

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:10.000
and we're talking about constitutional change and things that would affect that and overthrowing state government.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:20.000
And this is, more or less, looked upon as being anti-government or anti-treason or something.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:33.000
You see, we were, it could be met with all kinds of ways and then a legality attached to it as well by the governing sources.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:37.000
Did your parents ever find it necessary to ask you to stop doing this work?

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:43.000
No, in fact, my parents, I'm supported by my efforts. They saw the advances and they purchased me the cameras.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:34:00.000
I remember doing a very severe thunderstorm and doing those days, of course, you were taught to, and maybe even now, taught to kind of remain quiet doing a very heavy downpour in thunderstorm.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:10.000
I remember this particular time that as the storm was developing, I lay down on the floor and my mother lay it on the top of the bed.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:21.000
And as we were waiting for the storm to pass and we could cut off all the lights and my father is on a chair also and everybody's remaining quiet.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:33.000
And I remember this was my way. I had a captive audience there to sort of beg my mother for that camera that I had seen in the Seism Rulebook catalog.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:43.000
And so that's when I took the advantage of it and they ordered me a brownie hawk eye, I think, camera.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:51.000
And this was the camera, of course, with the flash unit attached with it. And at that time, I think $75 from Seism Rulebook.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:35:00.000
And this was the way that you got something because the stores in Orangeburg or Columbia, Charleston probably would not carry that.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:09.000
There were no camera stores as I remember even in the largest cities like Columbia, Charleston. So you would order things like this.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:27.000
The Margaret was not nearly as popular. Maybe there might have been in African-American society, maybe one out of 10 families might have had a camera.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:30.000
So me having a camera was very rare at the time.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:42.000
Let me look, we talked a little bit about Clarenne County and how it set an early, early path towards Brown.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:53.000
Orangeburg will be a place where immediately after Brown, you get an unusual movement, quickly emerged.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:36:04.000
And just before we get to that, I want to ask one more thing. I knew in early 1955, the Clarenne is also active in the Brown and the climate created by Brown.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:14.000
The political climate shifts on race, etc. becomes a very active consideration. You photographed the KKK rally.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Well, not exactly. I attended a KKK rally. Yes. It happened that I covered this particular stage of my life. I was a contributor to the Orangeburg Times in Democrat. I took pictures for them of Rex and I chased fires and things like that because they would pay me $5 for my photographs.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:40.000
And of course, anything happened in Orangeburg. I felt myself to be somewhat of a correspondent for them.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:43.000
And that was the standard everyday white newspaper.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:57.000
That is correct. Yes. So I remember this particular incident where I went to a basketball game in Wilkes High School and I took pictures for a yearbook in the newspaper, of course, which I was also the editor and that was also the photographer.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:13.000
And the Clarenne rally, which was held on the Bellvale Road, in a wooded area, was announced in the paper. And when I read it, without really thoroughly thinking a lot about it, I, and without asking my parents.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:22.000
And of course, I must have been about 14 because I knew I had my drivers license and of course I could drive and this gave me access to moving around and taking pictures.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:36.000
So I left the game and I said, well, I'll run by and see if that Clarenne rally, you know, not realizing that it was really held, not for blacks to attend, but really to intimidate people in the community, African-American community.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:47.000
So when I got there, the Clarenne rally was already over. But there remained and outfronted, there were about two or three cars. And one of the cars was a highway patrol car.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:38:05.000
And there was a truck, I think, and one of the cars, which I did not know about who belonged to. But what's standing there, at the end of the Clarenne rally, was this highway patrolman and the Grand Dragon, who had taken off his hood.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:16.000
And they were, they're talking and also they were putting out the remains of the cross burning because it was all over and everybody had left.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:23.000
So here I come, I parked my car on the Belve Road and I walk up to them and they looked at each other and looked back at me and they said, well, what is this guy?

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:30.000
You know, does he not know any better? So I go up to them and I said, I said, looks like everything is over.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:41.000
Something like that, I don't remember exactly what I said. But anyway, they were puzzled and confused in the fact that I'm here on this African-American, has come to take a picture of this.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:58.000
What they, oh, I remember, as when I asked them and they said, yeah, it's already over. Then I turned around to leave. And I was leaving. They called me back and said, well, do you want to take a picture of us here? And I said, yeah.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:17.000
So what happened? The cross, the burned out cross was then, it was laying on the ground. And then so the three of us re-irrected the cross and the hookuck clans dragged them and the high control and I re-irrected the cross.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:27.000
And they stood in front of it and I took a picture of them. So when I told, later I told my mother, you know, what I had done, she said, you, you know, she really kind of was very angry.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:36.000
And I was kind of, it was very angry because she realized that I had put myself in danger. But being so naive about, you know, the whole thing, it didn't occur to me.

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:45.000
And then, years later, they had put myself into the danger. And that's one of the pictures that, of course, I have lost. I cannot find my images of that today.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:52.000
But I often think about the fact that, you know, these were very dangerous times.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:40:08.000
On the other hand, there were a lot of instances where I, being an African-American of a lighter skin complexion, I find myself really baking, breaking barriers myself for my race.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:22.000
Because at, I think, 18 years old, I, and then really accelerating my interest in photography, I want to become a member of the South Carolina professional photographers of America.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:28.000
And there were no African-American members. And I read that they were meeting at Hilton Head South Carolina for a membership meeting.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:41.000
So I called up the membership chairperson, Dan Bohrn of Walter Barra, and asked him about attending. He said, well, I don't know. He said, we don't have any, you know, colored photographers.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:46.000
So he talked to someone, he called back, he said, sure, we'd be very happy to have you.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:57.000
So I found myself in Hilton Head South Carolina. And there is a picture, of course, that I have where we all standing together as a group. And of course, I'm the only African-American.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:26.000
And there were other incidents doing my life that I find myself kind of breaking barriers. And even though it's not open just because I try, just like when I tried to take the picture, and I tend to the Cooke-Cooke-Cling rally, that I find myself being accepted and led in or become a part of, leading up to doing my semester break when I was at Clapping University.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:49.000
I remembered I visited my aunt and uncle doing the semester break and read a newspaper that senator John F. Kennedy was going to be at the Roosevelt Hotel and to make an announcement. At this time, Kennedy, there was speculation as to whether he would become a candidate, as there were others also contemplating on running for the presidency, but he had not announced yet.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:42:10.000
This is about January 1960. And as it turned out, there I am in this room, in a ballroom, in downtown New York, and the security people noticed me. And at this time, you know, there are a few African-Americans in journalism, even with the New York Times, another very liberal newspaper at the time.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:31.000
And they walk over to the hotel, walk over to the, to where I am, brother, in the ballroom, and they began to remove me from the room. And just at the moment, they were putting me out, John, send to Kennedy, and his wife were coming up to the podium, and they stopped them.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:53.000
And he came over when we talked a few minutes, he gave me one of his cards, and he asked me about what, you know, where I was there and that kind of thing. And I told him that in my political science class at Clapping, we had discussed the fact that he might be a great president if he were to run, or he was to announce, if he was, was to announce.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:43:19.000
And anyway, he, after we talked for a few minutes, and again, here's, here's this room full of press, and we're, here I am, they're talking with the person that would later become the president of the United States. And anyway, he asked, he, he cleared two seats, and told me to sit down here, and I sat down by Chet Huntly and David Brinkley, who won the front row.

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:39.000
And this gave me a great, I didn't have a telephoto lens, and of course, most of the still press photographers were regular, they were, they, then situated in the back of the room, and the TV people had, of course, the best view.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:47.000
But all the still photographers were way back in the back. So this gave me very close, good close-up pictures of, then, Suntajan of Kennedy.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:44:08.000
The significance of me being there though, I think was, it was the most opportune time because it was at this press conference that he announced that he would be a candidate. And so, I sent my pictures to him at High End Support, Massachusetts, wherever he is on the campaign trail during the time on his road to the presidency.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:23.000
I get an invitation to attend. When he lands in Columbia, South Carolina, I'm the only press person allowed to go in the Carolina airplane, which was his tenth seat of plane that he used to fly around in campaign.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:32.000
And here I find myself, you know, in conversation, often with, again, a gentleman that becomes one of our greatest American presidents.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:49.000
So there's, you know, unbelievable story come true that I had that kind of association with a person that, again, on the background that Johnson, of course, the enactment of the Civil Rights Act, or so forth, lead from that.

00:44:49.000 --> 00:45:07.000
And but I was very much disturbed, of course, by his early death and all the things that happened as a result of that. But again, one of the most fascinating parts of my, you know, like growing up as a photographer, where there was events that surrounded that.

