01:23:42.640 --> 01:23:55.640
You've just mentioned the art against entrance to Clemson in 1963 and so you put me in mind of of of course Kennedy's assassination later in 1963 and I wonder I should ask kind of your reaction as you recall it to Kennedy's assassination.

01:23:55.640 --> 01:24:11.640
Well African Americans as well I think is majority of people in that observed in this community black and white are really were very very upset.

01:24:11.640 --> 01:24:21.640
I mean it was almost a bit some natural disaster had taken places I remember I mean people were crying everywhere it was a very emotional time.

01:24:21.640 --> 01:24:28.640
I remember they were having a special ceremony at state college and where people just sat in silence for a few minutes.

01:24:28.640 --> 01:24:40.640
So he was very but loved president and again doing his very short time in office had demonstrated willingness to try to change the image of this country and put on.

01:24:40.640 --> 01:25:09.640
Putting place some of the laws we talked about and I by way was invited to the inauguration but was unable to go I think I would have enjoyed that but for many reasons I wasn't able to go but but he put into place many of the things again that under president Johnson allow the Civil Rights Act of the 19 early 19 the mid 1960s to take place and of course then we have.

01:25:09.640 --> 01:25:19.640
Some of the great changes occurring in race relations in the United States doing that for your time and I think it came about because Kennedy said it in a motion.

01:25:19.640 --> 01:25:38.640
Let me ask about let's talk a little about the way the ways in which Orangeburg did not did and did not change through these years and I thought we might start that conversation in 61 you took an extraordinary photograph of two young African Americans on the step of.

01:25:38.640 --> 01:26:07.640
The way press security and church where I think they are met by the mayor of Orangeburg can you tell that story and what that represent yes to friends of mine Dorothy van and Emmanuel Hickson wanted to attend a church in downtown Orangeburg and I think for the experience and they were both from other states that they won being from Virginia and the other one being from.

01:26:07.640 --> 01:26:36.640
I think New York or maybe another state so on this particular morning I got a tip from someone that they that these two students were going to go to the I think sent Paul church in downtown Orangeburg and I got in my car I went down there but I didn't know which church they were at so I really just circled the area and finally I saw the students about to go out the street.

01:26:36.640 --> 01:26:55.640
About to go up the steps so I jumped out of my car left the door and I ran up the steps and they had already knocked on the door the doors closed and services had already begun and in a minute a person put their head out of the door it turned out to be a mere Clyde fair.

01:26:55.640 --> 01:27:14.640
At the time he was a member of that church but he was a mayor of the city of Orangeburg and I photographed a picture of the two students being rejected and I also observed him when he said that this is a segregated church you can't come in go worship with your own people.

01:27:14.640 --> 01:27:22.640
At this particular time in my life and this picture was also had a very powerful influence on my life as well at this particular time.

01:27:22.640 --> 01:27:42.640
Similarly my relationship with the state newspaper and the Times Democrat isn't one where I can actually sell pictures to them so what happened I thought this picture would be of great importance and I drove to Columbia South Carolina after I developed the pictures.

01:27:42.640 --> 01:27:54.640
At that time the Associated Press was located on the second floor of the state newspaper and I carried the picture into them and I think I sold it to them for $35.

01:27:54.640 --> 01:28:11.640
The next day around the world the picture was on publications in Germany or many countries in many other countries throughout the United States and many newspapers including the front page.

01:28:11.640 --> 01:28:32.640
I think that time the Washington Star which was the most prominent daily in Washington DC and I think in New York Times then it was in magazines and newspapers later on but on the day after again on the front page of papers around the world showing that this southern mayor refusing entrance to a church.

01:28:32.640 --> 01:28:55.640
It turned out that this helped people to realize that one of the most segregated places in America at any given time was on a Sunday morning anywhere in the South that African Americans could not attend even a church of their choice and so we were still living in a very segregated society.

01:28:55.640 --> 01:29:24.640
And what happened though after that picture appeared about a month by the way I had finished college at the time and I was continuing my studies I was working on my masses at South Carolina State College and I had still yet a deferment and the selective service called me in to for an interview.

01:29:24.640 --> 01:29:52.640
And I knew that that picture had really provoked them go caught their attention because as I sat down in their office on Doyle Street here in Orn'sburg for the interview one of the I think one of the ladies reached up in this vertical foul cabinet and as she reached up the pool the maneuver fold or containing my name and it opened accidentally the newspaper clipping.

01:29:52.640 --> 01:30:21.640
Then kind of floated like a feather falling to the floor so and that was my picture they had clipped from one of the newspapers so I knew that it was probably associated with what they later did in telling me that I had 30 days of clean up my fair that they were going to draft me so I was I didn't want to be in the army I joined the Air Force but I had to close my studio.

01:30:21.640 --> 01:30:49.640
I just kind of leave everything as it was and I felt again this was another way that they you might say finally got me because they had again worn my and this is the system you might say and some of the I'm talking about a general attitude but here here's one of the persons that's fanned in the fire as here's one of the ones that's publicizing these things that happened here's this person that's helping to wreck our way of life.

01:30:49.640 --> 01:30:56.640
I was in the mind of many people including the people that made up the selective service board.

01:30:56.640 --> 01:31:18.640
So you joined the Air Force? Yes. I was in Air Force I was in Air Force I was very short while while I was in Air Force I was injured doing flights doing my training and did not what I spent about a month and a half in a hospital and then I returned to Orangebury and then I had sold my studio before leaving going to the airport.

01:31:18.640 --> 01:31:45.640
So I had to kind of reestablish my business and all over again and get reestablished. I was going to be training other photographers I had a very good situation when I joined the Air Force I was going to be training other photographers in Florida but I had to finish my training in San Antonio, Texas but it was not to be and so I was glad to get in but I was also glad to get out.

01:31:45.640 --> 01:31:55.640
I'm happy for the historical record that you came back and kept photographing. Let me ask about a few more things and let's spend the last chunk of our time together talking about 68.

01:31:55.640 --> 01:32:24.640
Along the way you will photograph student protests on the steps of the State Capitol in Columbia in 62. Again, you made a very good point a few moments ago and what I wanted to acknowledge that this is a story more of continuity, episodic outbreaks but we do tend to focus on moments rather than the continuum but these landmarks in the air.

01:32:24.640 --> 01:32:49.640
The landmarks in the history here in South Carolina, the student protests in the State Capitol in 62, the desegregation of the University of South Carolina in 63. Very interesting challenge to racial segregation in the waiting rooms in Orangebury but a local hospital here in Orangebury in 63 with Miss Blackwell, Rackley Blackwell.

01:32:49.640 --> 01:32:59.640
And you're even approached by the White Citizens Council member to thank with an interesting offer along that span.

01:32:59.640 --> 01:33:02.640
Yes. Let's talk about that and then we'll talk about 68.

01:33:02.640 --> 01:33:18.640
Yes, I don't remember the exact year but I remember probably two times in my career being approached by persons associated with the citizen council and again since the employment situation was almost entirely in hands of influential white citizens.

01:33:18.640 --> 01:33:41.640
A Black person's fate was often determined by them and if you were known to be associated with the protest that was going on, you might be fired or something else might happen to you or you're alone, cold in all kinds of things to disrupt your life.

01:33:41.640 --> 01:34:00.640
And so I took a picture of a meeting of concerns citizens at Trinity Church and it was a picture of showing the faces because I took it from the standpoint of the podium back on the...

01:34:00.640 --> 01:34:19.640
And there must have been someone in the Black community who told someone in the citizen council that I had such a picture or it was known that when there was a meeting Cecil Williams probably had those pictures, one or the other.

01:34:19.640 --> 01:34:32.640
So this person that identified even up to today as Jack approached me and offered me, he just came up with all kinds of offers to see if I would sell those pictures to him and of course I never did.

01:34:32.640 --> 01:34:44.640
I thought that this was an attempted bribe and I went back to Reverend Matthew McCollum and I told him that this is what had happened and I had refused and that picture would never get to them.

01:34:44.640 --> 01:34:55.640
But mainly what they wanted to do was to take my picture and then see what faces they could identify, what members of the community could be identified that they would be able to put some kind of pressure.

01:34:55.640 --> 01:35:09.640
And mainly they were interested in maybe even from the leadership standpoint who were the ones that were often in the paper you would have a report from the papers that saying that, well hey, I'll black so this is Barnesburg, it's not them that's doing this.

01:35:09.640 --> 01:35:18.640
These outside agitators are comments and filetrators that wanted that would not let situations lie as they were.

01:35:18.640 --> 01:35:34.640
Although they may have been some of that still yet again, there was no comments and filetrators when this whole thing started and it was an African American movement that black citizens started.

01:35:35.640 --> 01:35:50.640
Let's tell me about the context for the Orangeburg Massacre in 68 at Bowling Island in relation to the segregation of the attempted desegregation at Bowling Island.

01:35:50.640 --> 01:35:57.640
How much did Orangeburg change after 64 and 65, the sub-rides act in Bowling Rights Act? How much did the community change?

01:35:57.640 --> 01:36:20.640
During the period of, say, 62 to 68, many things had, you had a lot of tokenism, you had a lot of blacks being hired, various places, you had most places after 1963, 64 and 65, the Bowling Rights Act and the other civil rights legislation taking place.

01:36:20.640 --> 01:36:31.640
You had a lot of changes taking place and they were felt here in South Carolina and they were very much appreciated and they were enjoying the benefits of those changes.

01:36:31.640 --> 01:36:39.640
But there were some pockets of resistance, some places, for example the churches still were largely segregated.

01:36:39.640 --> 01:36:55.640
And then also you had some places like Bowling Allies and restaurants that in South Carolina had still not welcomed African Americans to go into or to shop or whatever.

01:36:55.640 --> 01:37:19.640
And one here in Orangeburg was the Old Star Bowling Allie. Any student leaving State College of Claflin or any citizen walking uptown from the area of the campus and going up into the city of Orangeburg, if you were on Russell Street you would pass by a strip mall on the right-hand side and out front there was a sign that hung identifying this as the Old Star Bowling Allie but then it was a small sign that said white people were going to go to the city of Orangeburg.

01:37:19.640 --> 01:37:40.640
So if you were walking uptown to spend your money to purchase something you would pass by that sound every day or if you were riding by you would see it. It was large enough. It's about maybe a seven inch by three inch sign that said white only.

01:37:40.640 --> 01:37:59.640
And so this is one of the facilities that is not allowed African Americans. Some students at State College who have been driving to Columbia to Bowling and going other places because they were not welcome there decided that they would not take this anymore and they decided to go to the bowling alley and they were arrested.

01:37:59.640 --> 01:38:17.640
And then hearing about the arrests there were others from the campus that also joined. I get involved on about February the 6th, where I hear that there's a commotion going on at the bowling alley and that the students from State and Claflin.

01:38:17.640 --> 01:38:34.640
And being the yearbook photographer for State and Claflin, wherever the students were I was. I would catch all of their athletic activities, all of their student activities, all their license programs. And so here they were involved in a protest. So that's where I was.

01:38:34.640 --> 01:38:57.640
And what happened the students and the practice 250 or 300 students are in the area of the strip mall and they you have approximately 50 or 75 highway patrolman city police and others that are there and they're trying to tell the students to leave the area, you know, go back to your campus or you will be arrested.

01:38:57.640 --> 01:39:17.640
And just as all that was going on, I am a student pressed against a glass in one of the vacant stores in the mall and everyone's of course in a very packed or tight situation and the least movement caused the student to break this window.

01:39:17.640 --> 01:39:31.640
And as you broke the window, everybody heard the commotion and police authorities started raising their clubs as if somebody had maybe intentionally done this and they began trying to hit people. And so everyone started running away including myself.

01:39:31.640 --> 01:39:42.640
I had at that time a twin lens camera, you know, had it around my neck. And of course I started running too. In fact, I left my car because my car was parked out on Russell Street.

01:39:42.640 --> 01:40:01.640
I left the area and I turned left towards the campus because that's where the greater number of students were headed. And just as I turned by a former furniture store known as Sutcliffe's furniture store, I looked back and I saw a female student fall to the ground.

01:40:01.640 --> 01:40:11.640
And then I saw two city policemen start beating on her head with clubs just because of the fact that she had fallen, not because she had done anything and because she was running.

01:40:11.640 --> 01:40:22.640
So that just shows you the cruelty and the brutality that police authorities were using say this was three days before the what turned out to be the Orange Brick Massacre.

01:40:22.640 --> 01:40:35.640
On the night of the Orange Brick Massacre, I had returned from Columbia, South Carolina and of course I had been covering all the activities ongoing.

01:40:35.640 --> 01:40:49.640
And I came to State College from the area from again on college Avenue and right in front of Cloughfront, I could not get any further because there were police authorities blocking there.

01:40:49.640 --> 01:41:04.640
And I tried to circumvent where that blockage was and I went to another area but I couldn't get in there either. Then I had a couple of little other areas that I could that I knew that was on the campus itself from some other streets to get in but I could not get in.

01:41:04.640 --> 01:41:11.640
So there was no I found no way to be able to get on to the campus of State College on that particular evening.

01:41:11.640 --> 01:41:36.640
Later I would find out that might be unable to get there probably saved my life because doing the night, doing a time after the students had built a bonfire, nine highway patrolmen started creeping up under the campus of State College and they started firing their shotguns into a crowd of about 250 students.

01:41:36.640 --> 01:41:51.640
And ultimately they after I think about nine or 10 seconds of firing, you have the three students who were later found to be killed.

01:41:51.640 --> 01:42:01.640
Then you had about 27 injured and you have perhaps many, many more some of whom have never come forward that also receive a very minor injuries.

01:42:01.640 --> 01:42:16.640
And almost all of the injuries are injuries from the back. Jack Bass has a great book out called The Orange Bring Mask which tells the story in detail and he and Jack Anderson did a very good reportage on that.

01:42:16.640 --> 01:42:24.640
My book called Orange Bring 1968 also has the visual coverage on the pictures from that particular date.

01:42:24.640 --> 01:42:43.640
But the morning after the massacre I got in my car drove to the State College campus and there was an airy atmosphere surrounding the area where the students were the night before and where the killings had taken place.

01:42:43.640 --> 01:42:51.640
It was an overcast morning, it was very cold, I had on my overcoat and this is about 6, 30, 7 o'clock in the morning.

01:42:51.640 --> 01:43:00.640
And I noticed that the maintenance structure on the campus had arrived and they were picking up all of the debris to clean up the area.

01:43:01.640 --> 01:43:13.640
And so I looked down and I saw shotgun shells and other debris spread all over the air where the students had been killed and I started picking those shells up and putting them in my pockets.

01:43:13.640 --> 01:43:19.640
And then the maintenance truck would also was picking up other things at the same time.

01:43:19.640 --> 01:43:27.640
Later, after my picture appears in I think time and news week and in newspapers all over the United States.

01:43:28.640 --> 01:43:36.640
I should mention that I took a picture of the shells, I really stood it, I posed the picture of a student holding the shells.

01:43:36.640 --> 01:43:39.640
And I think I had about 7 or 8 or 9 shells.

01:43:39.640 --> 01:43:46.640
And later after this picture appeared in many publications, national publications around the United States.

01:43:47.640 --> 01:44:00.640
The Federal Bureau of Investigation confiscated the shells from me and they later were used as a trial is developed to try to highway patrolmen.

01:44:00.640 --> 01:44:09.640
And they laid the shells that I picked up to coming from 9 highway patrolmen who had actually fired or killed the students.

01:44:09.640 --> 01:44:17.640
As it turned out in a trial in Florence, South Carolina, the old 9 highway patrolmen were found not guilty.

01:44:17.640 --> 01:44:36.640
And to bring that up to today, I think that only a couple of years the FBI considered maybe reinvestigating reopening this particular case but they failed to do so as well.

01:44:36.640 --> 01:44:40.640
And it was also offered a job to be to join the FBI at that time.

01:44:40.640 --> 01:44:50.640
At this time in 1968 there were very few African Americans and the FBI agent who got the shells from me informed me that I'm J.E.G.A.

01:44:50.640 --> 01:44:57.640
who himself had asked him to ask me if I wanted to be an FBI agent.

01:44:57.640 --> 01:45:05.640
And of course I refused that offer because I didn't know whether it was a genuine effort or whether they wanted really just to have an effort.

01:45:05.640 --> 01:45:11.640
And it made me an informant out of me which I refused.

01:45:11.640 --> 01:45:18.640
In more recent times we've heard a case where some photographers were approaching the same where I was.

01:45:18.640 --> 01:45:29.640
Whenever I received a notice of that type, I usually would inform the local officers that this is taking place.

01:45:29.640 --> 01:45:48.640
And as I did with that particular, again I told Robert Matthew McCollum and James Sulton that had been approached by the FBI and also Oscar Butler who was also seemingly of interest to them because again he was the student.

01:45:48.640 --> 01:45:58.640
The university is over the student organizations on the campus and they felt that they...

01:45:58.640 --> 01:46:01.640
We're seeking information on him as well.

01:46:01.640 --> 01:46:10.640
And the FBI, again although investigating this particular case in my opinion failed to do the job that they should have done because there was no doubt who killed the students.

01:46:10.640 --> 01:46:16.640
The fact is that there were no guns found to belong to any students.

01:46:16.640 --> 01:46:27.640
And although an officer had been injured by a part of a railing from a house next door doing the time there were students there, still yet there was no massive effort.

01:46:27.640 --> 01:46:33.640
And anything to justify the highway patrolman really firing upon the students.

01:46:33.640 --> 01:46:40.640
And this incident came to be known as the only big massacre because that's exactly what it was. They were defenseless.

01:46:40.640 --> 01:46:42.640
They didn't have any weapons.

01:46:42.640 --> 01:46:53.640
And to today it's also unfortunately one of the stories about things happening this era that many publications and people really don't know about.

01:46:53.640 --> 01:46:57.640
It hadn't been reported in many publications other than my own.

01:46:57.640 --> 01:47:01.640
I think there are two books about it or mine and the one by Jack Bass.

01:47:01.640 --> 01:47:15.640
And it's nowhere nearly as well known as the Kent State students massacre where they were protesting also at the time again for the involvement of the United States in the...

01:47:15.640 --> 01:47:22.640
I think the Vietnam War where students were also fired upon by highway patrolman and also national guardsmen.

01:47:22.640 --> 01:47:30.640
I know that Justice Finney and well not then Justice Finney but he was then the head of the Human Relations Committee.

01:47:30.640 --> 01:47:37.640
Another member of both resigned in 1969 out of their frustration over the lack of prosecutorial effort in the war against the massacre.

01:47:37.640 --> 01:47:38.640
Yes.

01:47:38.640 --> 01:47:42.640
John, let's pause here for a moment.

01:47:42.640 --> 01:47:45.640
We're back after short break and we're going to finish today.

01:47:45.640 --> 01:47:55.640
I've approached very appropriately I think with a look at some of your work Mr. Williams and just some reflections as you have several volumes with the picture published.

01:47:55.640 --> 01:47:58.640
These are some pictures of...

01:47:58.640 --> 01:48:08.640
I think that I probably have probably more inside details than I think of any other civil rights publication I know.

01:48:08.640 --> 01:48:13.640
Again pictures coming from the inside of the movement but here are students getting out of jail.

01:48:13.640 --> 01:48:27.640
These are the photographs that often you don't see into other publications because again you see the major event or incident but again these are the kind of behind the scenes.

01:48:27.640 --> 01:48:35.640
Money was raised and being able to students out and here that you see them getting out of jail and some of the students have a jubilant look because...

01:48:35.640 --> 01:48:46.640
although they on sacrifice themselves the go to jail they're also happy to get out because jail conditions were very terrible at this time.

01:48:51.640 --> 01:48:59.640
One of the largest demonstrations in civil rights history and the largest number of arrests occurred at what is called the pink palace.

01:49:00.640 --> 01:49:02.640
Is there a way to turn to that?

01:49:02.640 --> 01:49:05.640
Turn to the pink palace.

01:49:06.640 --> 01:49:11.640
Now I was a jail here at the city police. This is where I went to jail twice.

01:49:11.640 --> 01:49:21.640
And of course usually the NWCP would bail me out and I was never even fully booked.

01:49:21.640 --> 01:49:26.640
I would be bailed out first because they wanted me to continue taking the photographs.

01:49:27.640 --> 01:49:33.640
But here are students in what is called the stockade of the pink palace.

01:49:33.640 --> 01:49:47.640
And one of the photographs associated with this was on the front pages of the York Times and around the world where at one time the largest number of demonstrators ever arrested in a mass civil rights protest was this particular one.

01:49:47.640 --> 01:49:50.640
388 I think were arrested.

01:49:50.640 --> 01:50:04.640
So many were arrested that it overfilled even this facility and even pinnitentiary buses were called in from Columbia to haul the students back to the pinnitentiary.

01:50:04.640 --> 01:50:09.640
So again this is about... I'm not sure what this is.

01:50:09.640 --> 01:50:10.640
1960.

01:50:10.640 --> 01:50:11.640
1960 correct, yes.

01:50:11.640 --> 01:50:17.640
That was the first real large, direct action protest at Greensboro.

01:50:18.640 --> 01:50:31.640
And I think what happened was if I remember what that photo shows is how demonstrators were funneled into a fence theory behind the jail.

01:50:31.640 --> 01:50:35.640
Yes. It was a cold February morning. I remember that and the students were wet.

01:50:35.640 --> 01:50:41.640
The water hoses were called in and they were wet and placed in these facilities.

01:50:42.640 --> 01:51:02.640
The other unique thing about America's civil rights movement, especially the events happening in the South in the deep South in South Carolina and among the students that I have associated with was the fact that students were well dressed often when they participated in a movement.

01:51:02.640 --> 01:51:08.640
The men would have on a shirt and tie and a coat and the young ladies were looking like they were going to church.

01:51:08.640 --> 01:51:11.640
So they were well dressed and they were well orderly.

01:51:11.640 --> 01:51:19.640
Then they were well behaved even before Martin Luther King's call for no passive resistance.

01:51:19.640 --> 01:51:30.640
So this is an underscore of the fact that they wanted to peacefully achieve these objectives of equality and justice and freedom for all.

01:51:32.640 --> 01:51:34.640
Is there any particular?

01:51:34.640 --> 01:51:37.640
No, really. There are some other things that really come with all that to be.

01:51:37.640 --> 01:51:50.640
This is a photograph that I have in my office. This is I think about 1963, Downtown Orangeburg and here you have 3000 people including my own mother who are part of a demonstration.

01:51:50.640 --> 01:51:59.640
They have really come here to pray for peace and tranquility and also for opportunities.

01:51:59.640 --> 01:52:12.640
And also asking I think one of the ministers who pray to ask that city authorities also employ black youth and employ black citizens.

01:52:12.640 --> 01:52:24.640
You have this time where you have almost no black city police, no blacks in the city council, no blacks in the county government, nothing.

01:52:24.640 --> 01:52:33.640
So it's still even in 1963 a very segregated area that we live in.

01:52:33.640 --> 01:52:47.640
I tried to with with out of the boxing Dixie produce a top quality book that would be representative of the dignity of the movement that occur.

01:52:47.640 --> 01:53:07.640
And the fact that here is my effort to bring too light some of the unsung heroes who started and kept the civil rights movement objectives ongoing.

01:53:07.640 --> 01:53:17.640
There is almost no picture of the people that most people associate with the civil rights movement Martin Luther King Rosa Parks, Jesse Jackson in my book.

01:53:17.640 --> 01:53:30.640
Here are unknown unsung heroes who are really making the movement happen and moving along and at the grassroots level of the movement.

01:53:30.640 --> 01:53:59.640
It starts with the beginning of the civil rights movement in Clarenting County and it goes through really the 2000 year 2008 or 2009 with my coverage of events that largely fall into the pursuit of African Americans trying to achieve.

01:53:59.640 --> 01:54:10.640
They're full citizenship in America and so this is my contribution hopefully to that effort.

01:54:10.640 --> 01:54:18.640
Let me know too for the record that there are two other books that you've published we mentioned one already Freedom and Justice and another.

01:54:18.640 --> 01:54:30.640
And the Orange Break Master again puts the faces to the movement and also it has the stories and interviews that persons injured.

01:54:30.640 --> 01:54:45.640
You have here stories of the persons who were actually shot and the words of how it was when they realized that they were bleeding and the very graphic illustrations.

01:54:45.640 --> 01:55:05.640
And again from the yearbook which I was a yearbook photographer time I tried to pull their picture of what were they involved in the time that this happened and to have some background to what went on.

01:55:06.640 --> 01:55:25.640
This is John Stroman who was again they tried to make a scrape goat of him and it went on tried to charge him with disobedience and riot charges.

01:55:25.640 --> 01:55:32.640
The only person jailed relative to the Orange Break Master was Cleveland sellers.

01:55:32.640 --> 01:55:54.640
Sellers was really jailed not for the events that happened in 1968 he was actually jailed for the incident that happened that I described earlier on February 6 where the police authorities are called into the bowling alley area.

01:55:54.640 --> 01:56:12.640
Because he was not even at the actual site when it first went on he was I think of walking by. Sellers today has moved from that era to really today being the president of Volis College.

01:56:13.640 --> 01:56:27.640
Mr Williams let me thank you so much for being so generous with your time and your work and all just extraordinary perspectives.

01:56:27.640 --> 01:56:31.640
Thank you, it's a very good part of this.

01:56:31.640 --> 01:56:33.640
Thank you for something.

01:56:33.640 --> 01:56:36.640
You the one that is I'm sorry we still own camera.

01:56:36.640 --> 01:56:39.640
We will just cut the one where we can stop there.

01:56:39.640 --> 01:56:49.640
